#X text 515 78 The [power~] object from ELSE is a power-law shaper gives us \, by default -pow(-in \, 1/p). For negative input \, it extends the usual definition and allows exponentiation of negative signal values. Try it also with samples and live input \, which is fun to do with any waveshaper by the way., f 48;
#X obj 638 367 f2s~ 10 1;
#X obj 689 245 f2s~;
#X text 30 25 A power function doesn't really work well and results in half wave or full wave rectification (that we'll see in the next example). A power function would originally give us a 'nan' (Not a Number) if a negative signal 'a' is raised by a non integer exponent 'b' \, and if you square it you only get positive values. Note that [pow~] gives us "0" instead of 'nan'., f 59;
